{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"650c9642-4a36-4324-9d3b-278c8c3b50c4","content":"Here's my analysis of the evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## Evaluation Performance Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading file contents via `System.IO.File` during evaluation is expensive — it blocks the evaluation thread on disk I/O. This runs on *every* evaluation (IDE refresh, design-time builds, etc.).\n\n**Fix:** Move file reading to a target at build-time, or use a task that reads the file only when needed.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis glob walks the *entire* directory tree. If the project sits inside a large repo or has `node_modules`/`.git`/package caches, evaluation time balloons as MSBuild enumerates every file.\n\n**Fix:** Scope the glob to specific extensions or subdirectories, and add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low-Medium Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA 3-level deep import chain (on top of the SDK's own imports). Each import adds file-open and parse overhead during evaluation. This is modest here but becomes significant in larger repos with dozens of levels.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order for fixes:** #1 > #2 > #3. The property function with file I/O is the worst offender since it forces synchronous disk access on every evaluation pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"73f867f1-ecbe-43e0-bb43-400176a72b7b","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"DBCF:2FF84E:A52BC16:B42997E:69FD39CC"},"id":"a39b8eb5-40e8-487f-b970-6b34b7225364","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:18:15.665Z","parentId":"6b3fbcdf-7bca-4a97-9e45-c97f3d49689d"}
